It also has features such as a beavertail grip safety and a manually operated thumb safety. In addition to these two safeties, the Ruger SR1911 also has a sear disconnect, slide stop and half-cock position. Although Colt's 80 series developed a trigger operated firing pin block safety, and Kimber and Smith & Wesson use a Swartz firing-pin safety, which is operated by the grip safety; the Ruger SR1911 pistol features a titanium firing pin and heavy firing pin spring, which negates the need for a firing pin block, offering an updated safety feature without compromising trigger pull weight.To improve quality, the stainless steel barrel and bushings are all produced from the same bar stock and on the same machine. Features such as an oversized ejection port and an extended magazine release enhance the performance of the weapon as well. The SR1911 also has a visual inspection port which allows for visual confirmation that the chamber is loaded.Manufacturer: RugerModel: SR1911Action: Single-ActionCaliber: .45 ACPBarrel: 4.5"

title: For Sale:  Yugo M48 Mauser
postcontent: Excellent condition Yugoslavian M48 8mm Mauser for sale. From what I can tell, all parts appear to be matching with the same serial number (stock, bolt, receiver, magazine floorplate, etc.). This rifle design was heavily based on the German K98k Mauser. Unlike the more prevalent M24 Yugo Mausers, this rifle has the more “conventional” turned down bolt handle. The rifle shoots fantastic and the 8mm is a very effective cartridge. This is a great way to get an excellent looking and shooting Mauser rifle without having to pay the high prices commanded by German K98s.For an additional $25 I will include an M48 bayonet with scabbard and frog. The serial numbers for the bayonet and scabbard match each other. For an additional $175 I will include a can of 340 rounds of Romanian 8mm surplus ammo. This ammo is steel cased and likely uses corrosive primers, but I have not experienced any issues out of the ammo it has performed well. As long as the proper cleaning procedures for shooting corrosive ammo is followed (be assured I always did with this rifle) then this is an excellent opportunity to purchase a bulk of surplus ammo that is quickly drying up at a reasonable price. As a bonus, every round of this ammo is pre-loaded into stripper clips for easy feeding into the rifle! The best price that I have been able to find online for 8mm ammo (including surplus) is ~ $0.50/round. FYI, the rifle case shown in the photo is not included.Asking $475 for just the rifle, $25 for the bayonet, $175 for the 340 rounds of ammoIf you would like to purchase just one of these items separate from the rest, let me know.$675 for everything together.If you have any questions, feel free to ask.

title: For Sale:  Used-Polish Pps 43 (ICN
postcontent: For Sale: Used Polish PPS 43 pistol. This firearm is in good condition (90+) with normal wear and handeling marks with a good clean bore.  This Pistol comes with 6 (35rd) magazines all in good working order, a period correct surplus sling, a surplus 3 mag pouch, Cleaning kit, and tactical carry case.   The history. The PPS43 (Pistolet-Pulemet Sudaeva, model of 1943 = Sudaev submachine gun) was born as an answer for the need of a weapon that would be more compact and mobile than the PPSh-41, which was in use then by the Soviet Army. The PPSh-41 was somewhat too long to be used by tank crews, mobile recon groups and paratroopers. In late 1941, the Red Army issued a request for a new, more compact SMG. Designer Sudaev initially designed his new SMG in 1942 and it was adopted under the designation of PPS42. Next year he refined the design and this final model was designated as PPS43. This SMG was manufactured in significant numbers, with nearly 2 million PPS43 weapons manufactured between 1943 and 1946. The PPS43 is sometimes referred to as the best SMG of World War II. After WWII, it was widely exported to pro-Soviet regimes around the world and widely copied. The PPS43 was license-produced in Poland starting in 1946.   Today… Pioneer Arms together with, I.O. Inc., has redesigned this historical firearm to shoot from a closed bolt position. The safety is located at the front of the trigger guard. The receiver and barrel shroud are made from stamped steel. The rear sight is an L-shaped flip type and is marked for 100 and 200 meters distance. The front sight is a fixed blade. The barrel is equipped with a simple muzzle brake. This firearm is an ATF approved pistol. The stock has no function and is permanently fixed in its folded closed position. this pistol is manufactured at the famed Radom Plant in Poland by Pioneer Arms. All parts and components are Polish made. The PPS43-C pistol comes with a curved box magazine which holds up to 35 rounds.
